1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,000
What if you were Donald Trump?

2
00:00:02,000 --> 00:00:15,000
Everything about Donald John Trump's life is exactly as it happened, the father, the money, the queen's apartment, the borrowed millions, the deals, the failures, the comeback, the gold elevator, the white house.

3
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:18,000
The only thing that changes is the pronoun.

4
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:20,000
You are him.

5
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:22,000
You always were.

6
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:25,000
This is your story, told to your face.

7
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:28,000
You are born in June 1946.

8
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:31,000
Queens, New York.

9
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:33,000
Not Manhattan, Queens.

10
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:39,000
This distinction will bother you for the rest of your life, though you'll never admit it out loud.

11
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:41,000
Your father is Fred.

12
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:46,000
Fred builds affordable housing in Brooklyn and Queens and calls it an empire.

13
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:52,000
You watch him count money at the kitchen table and decide that whatever he's doing, you're going to do it bigger.

14
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:53,000
Louder.

15
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:56,000
With your name on the outside of the building.

16
00:00:57,000 --> 00:00:59,000
You are not a subtle child.

17
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:06,000
You are the loudest person in every room you enter, and you enter every room as though you have already been announced.

18
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:11,000
School is something that happens to you between the ages of being loud and being louder.

19
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:21,000
You attend the New York Military Academy at 13, not because you're troubled, exactly, but because your parents sense that regular institutions are not equipped for whatever you are.

20
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:23,000
You thrive there.

21
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:25,000
You like uniforms.

22
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:27,000
You like rankings.

23
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:32,000
You like knowing who's in charge and making sure everyone knows it's you.

24
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:35,000
College is for them, Ben Warden.

25
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:38,000
You graduate in 1968.

26
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:41,000
You tell people you graduated first in your class.

27
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:43,000
There is no record of this.

28
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:46,000
You don't consider this a lie.

29
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:48,000
You consider it a preview.

30
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:52,000
Your father gives you a small loan of a million dollars.

31
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:55,000
You will later describe this loan as modest.

32
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:59,000
$1,974.

33
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:01,000
You take it and build.

34
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:12,000
You build in Manhattan because Manhattan is where the real money is, and you have decided, with the certainty of a man who has never seriously been told no, that you belong there.

35
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:14,000
The Grand Hyatt.

36
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:15,000
Trump Tower.

37
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:17,000
Fifth Avenue.

38
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:24,000
You put your name on the outside of the building and letters the size of a reasonable car, and somehow the city lets you do it.

39
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:27,000
The eighties are very, very good.

40
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:30,000
You are on every magazine cover.

41
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:39,000
People who have never met you talk about you at dinner parties, and not always in the way you prefer, but you have already figured out that being talked about is the whole game.

42
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:41,000
You buy a yacht.

43
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:43,000
You name it after yourself.

44
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:45,000
You buy a helicopter.

45
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:48,000
You name it after yourself.

46
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:51,000
There is a pattern here and you are fully committed to it.

47
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:56,000
You write a book called The Art of the Deal and it sells four million copies.

48
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:04,000
You did not write most of it, but your name is on the cover, and by now you have learned that having your name on things is more or less the same as having done them.

49
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:08,000
Then the nineties arrive, and they arrive hard.

50
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:10,000
The Casinos fail.

51
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:12,000
Not one casino.

52
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:14,000
Three casinos.

53
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:25,000
The Taj Mahal, the Plaza, the Castle, all in Atlantic City, all carrying your name in oversized letters, all declaring bankruptcy within years of each other.

54
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:30,000
You opened a casino and lost money at it, which is statistically difficult to do.

55
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:35,000
The casino is the one business mathematically designed to favor the house.

56
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:37,000
You were the house.

57
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:39,000
The airline fails.

58
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:42,000
The mortgage company fails.

59
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:47,000
The state company, and yes, there is a state company, fails.

60
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:50,000
You owe $900 million.

61
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:58,000
The banks don't foreclose because they owe you $900 million, which means you are, paradoxically, too broke to be bankrupt.

62
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:01,000
You call this a negotiating position.

63
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:04,000
Remarkably, it works.

64
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:06,000
You restructure.

65
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:15,000
You license your name to buildings you don't own, attach your face to products you don't use, and spend 15 years convincing the world that the brand survived intact.

66
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:18,000
The brand survives intact.

67
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:21,000
In 2004 you get a television show.

68
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:23,000
The Apprentice.

69
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:30,000
You sit at the head of a boardroom table and fire people with two words that somehow become the most recognizable phrase in America.

70
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:33,000
You are not playing a character.

71
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:41,000
You are playing a perfected version of yourself, decisive, powerful, unbothered by nuance, and the audience loves it.

72
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:43,000
14 seasons.

73
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:46,000
Millions of viewers.

74
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:52,000
The show does something the buildings never quite managed. It makes you famous to people who have never been to New York.

75
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:54,000
Famous to everyone.

76
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:58,000
Famous in a way that money alone cannot buy.

77
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:00,000
This is where it gets interesting.

78
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:04,000
This is where the story stops being about real estate.

79
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:16,000
Because somewhere between the 14th season of a reality television show and the moment you start genuinely believing you could run the country, somewhere in that gap between entertainment and ambition, something shifts.

80
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:21,000
You have spent your entire life performing the role of the most powerful man in the room.

81
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:27,000
And it occurs to you, slowly then all at once, that there is one room you have never been in.

82
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:30,000
One room with no one above you.

83
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:33,000
One room you cannot put your name on, yet.

84
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:39,000
And that's where your story ends, and where the story of what you accidentally started begins.

85
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:50,000
In June 2015, at the age of 69, he wrote a golden escalator down to a lobby full of paid supporters and announced he was running for president of the United States.

86
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:53,000
The political establishment laughed.

87
00:05:53,000 --> 00:05:58,000
The political news gave him $12 billion in free air time because he was good television.

88
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:04,000
This was, in retrospect, one of the more consequential mistakes in the history of broadcasting.

89
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:17,000
He won the Republican primary by doing something no one had done before, treating every debate like a boardroom firing, every rally like a stadium concert, and every press conference like a negotiation where he was already winning.

90
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:21,000
16 other candidates tried conventional politics.

91
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:27,000
He tried a different genre entirely, one that looked less like a campaign and more like a season finale.

92
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:31,000
His opponents were prepared for a political campaign.

93
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:35,000
He was running a media franchise with electoral consequences.

94
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:38,000
November 8, 2016.

95
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:40,000
He won.

96
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:44,000
The transition was, by all measurable standards, chaotic.

97
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:51,000
Staff came and went through the West Wing at a pace that suggested either a revolving door or a fire drill.

98
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:54,000
14 Chiefs of Staff

99
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:57,000
19 Communications Directors

100
00:06:57,000 --> 00:07:07,000
A national security adviser who lasted 24 days, a record that still stands, largely because no one has tried to break it out of a sense of basic dignity.

101
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:13,000
He governed the way he built, loudly, with his name on everything, convinced that the loudness was the point.

102
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:19,000
He signed executive orders at a desk in front of cameras, holding them up like report cards.

103
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:22,000
He called foreign leaders from his personal cell phone.

104
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:27,000
He hosted state dinners at his own golf club and charged the government for the rooms.

105
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:30,000
Some people called this corruption.

106
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:32,000
He called it efficiency.

107
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:36,000
The difference, he would tell you, was branding.

108
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:39,000
He renegotiated trade deals.

109
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:45,000
He held rallies in arenas as though the campaign never ended, because for him it never did.

110
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:47,000
The campaign was the governing.

111
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:50,000
The governing was the brand.

112
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:54,000
It was never entirely clear where one stopped and the other began.

113
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:57,000
A pandemic arrived in 2020.

114
00:07:57,000 --> 00:08:03,000
He suggested, on national television, that injecting disinfectant might be worth looking into.

115
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:09,000
The manufacturer of the disinfectant issued a statement asking the public not to inject their product.

116
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:12,000
This had never happened before.

117
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:18,000
Not once in the entire history of cleaning products had a company been forced to issue that particular warning.

118
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:24,000
He lost the 2020 election by 7 million popular votes and 74 electoral votes.

119
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:27,000
He did not agree with this assessment.

120
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:33,000
He spent the following months arguing, litigating, and hosting rallies in which he argued some more.

121
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:35,000
Democracy wobbled.

122
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:37,000
January 6th happened.

123
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:40,000
History took careful notes.

124
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:43,000
He ran again in 2024.

125
00:08:43,000 --> 00:08:46,000
He won again in 2024.

126
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:55,000
He became the first convicted felon elected to the American presidency and responded to this fact with the energy of a man who considers it a personality asset.

127
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:57,000
He was probably right.

128
00:08:57,000 --> 00:09:10,000
At 78 years old, he returned to the White House, the oldest person ever elected to the office, carrying 34 felony convictions and roughly the same energy as a man who has just won an argument he started himself.

129
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:19,000
He came back with the same certainty he had carried into every boardroom, every building, every sentence he had ever begun and refused to let someone else finish.

130
00:09:19,000 --> 00:09:22,000
The world had changed around him repeatedly.

131
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:24,000
He had not changed at all.

132
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:29,000
Whether that was the secret or the problem depended entirely on who you asked.

133
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:33,000
You always knew your name would be on the biggest things.

134
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:36,000
You just never specified what kind of things.

135
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:39,000
Not the buildings, necessarily.

136
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:41,000
Not the stakes.

137
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:43,000
Not the show.

138
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:45,000
Something bigger.

139
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:51,000
Something that couldn't be foreclosed on, couldn't be licensed away, couldn't be restructured in bankruptcy court.

140
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:58,000
A name on history itself, permanent, impossible to revalue, impossible to take back.

141
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:05,000
The question history is still working out as whether that was the plan all along or whether the plan was simply never to have one.

